<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">As with any trade skill, you should be focusing on int and wis.  The int is obvious because you need it for your casting anyway.  That will govern how fast your skill rises.  Wis governs success rate, but use magic items instead of sacrificing your int or you won't be as effective a wizard.  You will also want charisma gear later to raise merchant prices, and perhaps some shaman buffs for charisma when you sell.<p>

Wizzies have a good deal because of teleporting later on for getting components, but can't carry heavy stuff.  Jewelry is not a good one because you can't enchant metals yourself.  Tailoring pelts are too heavy, but cured silk would fetch you a good price without being too much to carry.  You might try tailoring then.  Baking also is good and you can increase this skill very cheaply, although it has none of the glamour that smithing does.  In the end, something will appeal to you, but don't sacrifice your main playing skills for a trade skill.  <p>

Good luck to you :)<p>

Merro<br>
19 Shaman<br>
Master Baker<br>
Master Smith<br>
Struggling Tailor (oh god)<br>
Mediocre everything else (oh but I can swim as well as a baby iksar ;)<br>
Lanys T'Vyl</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
